      <div xml:id="NA176-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu parattait talaivi pāṅkikkup pāṅkāyiṉār kēṭpa viṟalikku uraittatu.
            (ET, EV: talaiviyiṉ ... parattai viṟalikkuc colliyatu.)</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the other woman said to the dancing girls so that those close to the one who is close to HER would hear.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA176">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ennayan tuṟaivi yāyiṉ yānayantu</l>
<l>            nalkiṉam viṭṭate ṉalattō ṉavvayiṟ</l>
<l>            cālpi ṉaḷitta laṟiyā tavaṭkavaḷ</l>
<l>            kātala ḷeṉṉumō vuraitticiṟ ṟōḻi</l>
<l>            niraitta yāṉai mukattuvari kaṭuppap </l>
<l>            pōtupoti yuṭainta voṇceṅ kāntaḷ</l>
<l>            vāḻaiyañ cilampiṉ vampupaṭak kuvaii</l>
<l>            yāḻōrt taṉṉa viṉkura liṉavaṇ</l>
<l>            ṭaruvi muḻaviṉ pāṭō ṭorāṅku</l>
<l>            meṉmela vicaikkuñ cāraṟ </l>
<l>            kuṉṟa vēlitta muṟaivi ṉūrē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>When she longed for us permanently, we, longing [for her],</l>
<l>granted it.<note place="foot">Here, too, syntax and message are enigmatic. Since in the beginning there is no direct object for <term xml:lang="ta">nalkiṉam</term>, and below there is no verb for <term xml:lang="ta">ūr</term>, it seems best to read a circular construction. The point might be, as T.V.G. affirms, that the rival woman allows the man to go home (at the time the maid has been sent with the message of the end of the wife's menstruation), or that the two women in question are about to meet in the place of the one who is "<term xml:lang="ta">ennayantu uṟaivi</term>". See, however, the b version which construes differently.</note> What has been let off on that side, by [our] good man?(?)<note place="foot">My suggestion is to split at the end of line 2, and to read a question as to what has been said by the man, here called <term xml:lang="ta">nalattōṉ</term>, possibly ironically, referring to the fact that the usual situation is turned upside down: the woman speaking is the one with the power to act, condescening to see the other one, presumably his wife.</note></l>
<l>Does it say “she is full of love for her,</l>
<l rend="indent3">who doesn't know how to take care of [her] status?” – speak, friend<note place="foot">So, the situation seems to be the following: the woman speaking is not the house-wife, but a rival. She asks her confidante what the man has been telling her concerning his wife, the point being that the house-wife (often depicted as not knowing how to defend herself) has uttered a wish of seeing her rival, and he is affirming that there is goodwill also on the other side, i.e. he has uttered the conviction that his lover is also willing to be favourable towards his wife.</note></l>
<l>– the village of their abode, with fences, in the hills,</l>
<l rend="indent3">on a slope, where soft soft [tones] are sounding:</l>
<l rend="indent">the bees in groups with pleasing voices, as if one listened to the lute,</l>
<l rend="indent">singing as one with the drum of the waterfall,</l>
<l rend="indent2">while heaped so as to be unstable on the banana[-grown] mountain side</l>
<l rend="indent2">are the bright red Malabar-lilies that have broken the pack of [their] buds,</l>
<l rend="indent3">resembling the lines in the faces of elephants put in a row.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="1-4b">
<l>    When she remained longing for us, we, longing [for her]</l>
<l> 	have granted letting go of my good man to that place.</l>
<l>     Does it (the village) say 'she is full of love for her</l>
<l> 	who doesn't know how to take care of [her] status?' – speak, friend.</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
